<br>
But I digress, for any number of words would not be fit to describe the hell and torment that is Doomfire. Never the less, I beg this of you: Do not be mislead by the following tale into garnishing some damned foolish idea that you yourself will find glory and treasure in these lands - for I would ever-so hate losing you as a patron as you burned in agony for all eternity, under the unforgiving eyes of the minions of Ro...<br>
<br>
There now, having that unpleasantness over with, shall we be moving along? Very good then -- but where to begin? Well let me see now -- hmm, yes, perhaps the first towering demon of seething fire we dispatched that night? Ah-ha, I thought that might peak your interest. Well then, there we shall start.<br>
<br>
From various books and tomes our scholars had gathered in the Grand Library of Knowledge, we had discovered the name of the one who stood in our way. Though he was large, fiery and unpleasant looking in general, I must admit it was the large, fiery and unpleasant claws that drew the bulk of my attention. The Guardian of Doomfire scowled at us from across the courtyard, but held its post, unwilling to waste it's might on any but those who dared to challenge the reign of his Master - unfortunately for the Guardian, confrontation with his Master was our sole purpose.<br>
<br>
With blades drawn and powerful death-magics weaved, we informed the Guardian of our challenge to his Master. As our final assaults destroyed his mind and body, the Guardian accepted the challenge we had laid forth against the one he had failed to protect. As the remains of his body dropped to the burning stoneclad ground, his last breath spat what appeared to be a small incantation -- but let me tell you, what this incantation wrought was anything but small. <br>
<br>
As the last of the indecipherable sounds passed the Guardian's lips, the ground shook with the stampeding of what felt to be a hundred giants. Accompanied by the howls of as many fiends of fire as had presently been awoken, I must confess our spirits wavered for a brief moment - for while none of us knew what waited beyond the Arch of Fennin, we all knew well enough.<br>
<br>
It was, however, a matter of seconds before warcries broke out from our own camp. Our own rage built, and we again remembered our purpose, and that to flee would be worse than death to we who crave absolute control over the Elements...<br>
